    <abstract>formation of the Chinese manuscrpt canon (ca. 400-597): pp. 15-21
    list of Dunhuang manuscripts (p. 17) which constitute the remains of a canon copying project, executed by scribe officials upon imperial order, dated to 511-514, supervised by Linghu Chongzhe 令狐崇哲.
    Afterwards: Wei Shou (齊三部一切經願文; Bei Qi) and Wang Bao (周經藏願文), both T.2103, 52: 257a19-b16, private projects.
    Before: one scroll has remained (S.996, dated 497) of Feng Xi's 馮熙(Feng Jinguo 馮晉國; died 495) project (a member of the imperial house of the Northern Wei), who copied 10 canons, each with 1464 scrolls.</abstract>
